      <subsection xml:id="electricity-transistors-and-ics">
         <title>Transistors and ICs</title>
         <p>A <term>transistor</term> is a semiconductor device that acts as an electronic switch or amplifier. It can control the flow of electric current between its two main terminals, known as the collector and emitter, by using a small current at its third terminal, called the base.  Transistors are used for amplification and switching purposes.and are the building blocks of modern electronics.</p>
         <p>The most common variety of transistor is the <term>bipolar junction transistor</term> (BJT), which has two variations: <term>NPN</term> and <term>PNP</term>.  In an NPN transistor, current flows from the emitter to the collector when a small current is applied to the base. A PNP transistor is the opposite of an NPN transistor.  In a PNP transistor, current flows from the collector to the emitter when a small current is applied to the base.</p>
